rived from a Russian-influenced transliteration of <i>grushka</i> ‘pear, pear tree’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gray","meanings":["English, Scottish, and Irish (especially Eastern Ulster; of Norman origin): habitational name from Graye in Calvados, France, named from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Graec(i)us</i>, meaning ‘Greek’ + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>. This is probably the chief source of the surname in Britain.","English: nickname for someone with gray hair or a gray beard, from Middle English <i>grey</i> (Old English <i>grǣg</i>, <i>grēg</i>) ‘gray’. In Ireland it has been used as a translation of various Gaelic surnames derived from <i>riabhach</i> ‘brindled, gray’, including <b>Mac Giolla Riabhaigh</b>; see   McGreevy  . In North America, this surname has assimilated names with similar meaning from other languages.","French: habitational name from Gray in Haute-Saône or Le Gray in Seine-Maritime."]},{"name":"Greiwe","meanings":["German: possibly a nickname from Middle High German <i>greibe</i> ‘sharp, tangy, dour’. Compare   Grey  ."]}]},{"name":"Katherina","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Katherine</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Katherina de Grey was born about 1350, in Ruthin, Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Alienor le Strange. She had at least 2 sons with Sir William de Lucy Knight."},"et":{"about 1350–":"umbes 1350–Surnud","1350–Female":"1350–Surnud","1362–1440":"1362–1440","1353–1401":"1353–1401","1373–1415":"1373–1415","1423–1460":"1423–1460","1328–1396":"1328–1396","1415":"1415","1423":"1423","1401":"1401","1353":"1353","1396":"1396","1440":"1440","1373":"1373","1362":"1362","1460":"1460","1350":"1350","about 1350":"umbes 1350","1328":"1328","Charlecote, Warwickshire, England":"Charlecote, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Charlcote Manor Charlecote, Warwickshire, England":"Charlecote, Warwickshire,